All of my Vegas reviews come from business trips, expenses paid.
So know that "price isn't the issue.
" I just want good food and service.
And for me, it's "fair expectation.
" If I'm at a $30 to $50 entree restaurant, then my expectations are obviously higher than if I'm stopping at a fast food location.
And if I'm taking clients to a $50 to $150 per person fooderie... than the entrees better reflect it.
Unfortunately, this is about a specialty fish restaurant in a well known hotel that doesn't deliver....... at least for me.
Buzios, in Brasil, is a historical fishing village, known for great seafood.
Buzios, the restaurant at the Rio, is under-whelming.
My expectations were dashed against the rocks, and my vision of having an exceptional fish meal were never met.
What the he** happened to Vegas?
You either have to pay huge "monies" for a good meal in a superficially special location, or, well, I just don't know anymore.
This isn't the Rio Hotel that I remember when they opened, and the current lack of "excitement" in the hotel has extended itself to Buzios.
We ordered the halibut, blackened.
Best thing at the meal was my baked potato, smothered in those assorted grilled mushrooms.
Those were my two sides.
And unfortunately, the sides overshadowed the entree.
Here in South Orange County, I can get a better fish meal at California Fish Grill in Foothill Ranch.... and for about $15.
We paid about $30 per person at Buzios, and all I could do was shake my head in a sad sorta' way, wondering if the Rio Buffet might have had more fish for about the same $$$?
Our halibut steak, as small as it was, just didn't have flavor.
I was expecting a thick, large steak.
And I would have paid more for better.
Buzios, at the Rio, is convenient if you're staying there, don't want to leave the property, and just want to get something to eat before going back to your room, or the casino.
I wish I could be more "excited" about it.
Sorry to say, I don't yet have a great family style fish house in my "Vegas black book.
" If you know of a place, let me know.
I've taken clients to Joe's Prime Steak at Ceasar's Forum, but that runs me about $100 minimum per client every time I go, and I'm not always with clients.
So that's not my idea of a low key, family-reasonable $$$ accessible fish joint.
And Landry's on Sahara has low ratings from yelpers.
So I'll just keep looking, I guess?

